@ \chapter{Level 1 swappable data}

\texttt{level1.bin} is the flat memory image loaded from tracks 5--9
when the game selects level~1.  It is extracted from the \texttt{.dsk}
by [[.claude/scripts/extract_level1.py]] (phase~0 of the loader's
[[PAGE_TABLE_RELOAD]]) and covers the full address window
[[$0000]]--[[$BDFF]] (48640 bytes).  Only the ``level-1 swappable pages''  % TODO-SYM: $BDFF
hold real bytes; every non-level page stays at [[$00]]:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$0200]] (1 page) --- initial game-data tables restored by
  [[FIRST_BOOT]] from [[ZP_SAVE]].
\item [[$1300]]--[[$18FF]] (6 pages) --- per-level attract/beam code  % TODO-SYM: $1300 $18FF
  (already documented in \texttt{drol.bin}: [[BEAM_UPDATE]] [[$130A]],
  [[ENEMY_A_ADVANCE]] [[$13D6]], [[ENEMY_A_DRAW]] [[$1423]],
  [[ATTRACT_ANIM_1]]..[[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]] [[$17A6]]--[[$188A]]).  % TODO-SYM: $188A
\item [[$6700]]--[[$72FF]] (12 pages) --- per-level game-engine and  % TODO-SYM: $6700 $72FF
  attract entry code (already documented in \texttt{drol.bin}:
  [[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]] [[$7208]], [[ATTRACT_LOOP]] [[$7263]],
  [[START_ATTRACT]] [[$72A3]]; earlier pages hold enemy-AI data).
\item [[$7500]]--[[$7AFF]] (6 pages) --- screen-row lookup tables and  % TODO-SYM: $7500 $7AFF
  sprite sub-sections consumed by the draw routines.
\item [[$8C00]]--[[$BDFF]] (50 pages, \emph{not} present in  % TODO-SYM: $8C00 $BDFF
  \texttt{drol.bin}) --- the bulk of the level-1 content: per-level
  sprite tables ([[ATTRACT_SPR]] / [[ATTRACT_SPR2]] at [[$B002]]/[[$B006]]
  with pointers into [[$B500]]--[[$BC]]\textit{xx}), the ``Broderbund''  % TODO-SYM: $B500 $BC
  attribution strip at [[$BCF1]], and the end-of-game handler  % TODO-SYM: $BCF1
  [[GAME_OVER]] at [[$BDA0]].
\end{itemize}

All of the shared pages ([[$0200]], [[$1300]]--[[$18FF]], [[$6700]]--[[$72FF]],  % TODO-SYM: $1300 $18FF $6700 $72FF
[[$7500]]--[[$7AFF]]) match \texttt{drol.bin} byte-for-byte because  % TODO-SYM: $7500 $7AFF
\texttt{drol.bin} is itself a snapshot taken after the loader has
deposited the level-1 pages into their run-time addresses.  The
only pages unique to \texttt{level1.bin} are [[$8C00]]--[[$BDFF]], the  % TODO-SYM: $8C00 $BDFF
high bank that the game only ever sees after level-1 loading
completes.

\section{Structure}

The \texttt{level1} target is maintained separately from
\texttt{drol} so we can verify the on-disk level bytes in isolation.
Most of the image is still raw \texttt{HEX} blobs at this stage; the
plan is to replace them one chunk at a time as level-specific routines
are reverse engineered.

Chunks that also live inside \texttt{drol.bin} (e.g.\ [[START_ATTRACT]],
[[ATTRACT_LOOP]], [[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]]) could in principle be shared
between the two collections via chunk references.  For now, the
\texttt{level1} target inlines the exact same bytes as a raw
\texttt{HEX} blob so the two targets are structurally independent
--- a good place to experiment without perturbing the known-good
\texttt{drol} build.  Future sessions are expected to carve out code
chunks at [[$72A3]]/[[$7208]]/[[$7263]] and share them via chunk references.

\section{The attract-mode title sprite pointers}

Two pointer tables at [[$B002]] and [[$B006]] (low bytes) with their high
bytes at [[$B082]]/[[$B086]] feed the attract-mode sprite draws:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[ATTRACT_SPR2]] ([[$B002]]/[[$B082]], 4 entries) --- consumed by
  [[ATTRACT_ANIM_2]].  Entries point at [[$B571]], [[$B59B]],  % TODO-SYM: $B571 $B59B
  [[$B5C5]], [[$B5E1]].  Sprite byte counts are [[$2A]]/[[$2A]]/[[$1C]]/[[$1C]]  % TODO-SYM: $B5C5 $B5E1 $2A $1C
  respectively (W=2,H=14 and W=1,H=14) --- the tall drifting
  silhouettes that sweep across the attract playfield.
\item [[ATTRACT_SPR]] ([[$B006]]/[[$B086]], 2 entries used by
  [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]] at [[$1844]]; additional entries are consumed by
  unrelated callers).  Entries point at [[$B5FD]], [[$B665]].  [[$B5FD]] is a  % TODO-SYM: $B5FD $B665
  [[$68]]-byte sprite (13 bytes/row $\times$ 8 rows; [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]]  % TODO-SYM: $68
  draws it with W=12,H=8).  [[$B665]] is [[$18]] bytes (3 bytes/row  % TODO-SYM: $B665
  $\times$ 8 rows, W=2,H=8).
\end{itemize}

A third consumer --- the extras-stash animation inside
[[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]] at [[$7208]] --- uses a hardcoded [[$B67D]] pointer  % TODO-SYM: $B67D
with W=6,H=14 (98 bytes).  That sprite is the extra-life glyph the
game-over sequence ticks once per remaining extra life.

Rendered forms of the two [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]] sprites (the only ones
whose dimensions are derivable from static code without simulating the
attract-mode ZP animation) are in Figure~\ref{fig:attract_spr_renders}.
The [[$B5FD]] shape is drawn with width~13 bytes --- the wide ``double  % TODO-SYM: $B5FD
band'' graphic that flies across the attract screen; the [[$B665]] shape  % TODO-SYM: $B665
is a narrow 3-byte-wide creature sprite.

